{{Jainism}}
'''Kumudendu Muni''' ({{lang-kn|ಕುಮುದೆಂದು ಮುನಿ}}) was a ''[[Digambara monk]]'' who authored [[Siribhoovalaya]], a unique multi-lingual literary work. Scholars are divided about when he lived and not much is known about him. It is believed that he was the spiritual teacher of King [[Amoghavarsha]] and a disciple of [[Virasena]] and [[Jinasena]]. He is said to have lived around thousand years ago. Pandit Yellappa Shashtri was the first one to decipher his creation, ''[[Siribhoovalaya]]''. Karlamangalam Srikantaiah, the editor of the first edition, claims that the work may have been composed around 800 AD.

==Biography==
Kumudendu Muni was a ''[[Digambara monk]]'' who authored [[Siribhoovalaya]], a unique multi-lingual literary work. Scholars are divided about when he lived and not much is known about him. It is believed that he was the spiritual teacher of King [[Amoghavarsha]] and a disciple of [[Virasena]] and [[Jinasena]].<ref>[http://www.srikanta-sastri.org/siribhoovalaya-an-opinion/4580668143 Scholarly opinion of S. Srikanta Sastri on "SIRIBHOOVALAYA"]</ref> He is said to have lived around thousand years ago. Pandit Yellappa Shashtri was the first one to decipher his creation, ''[[Siribhoovalaya]]''.<ref>{{citation|last1=Jain |first1=Anil Kumar|title=Creativity in Cryptography: An Epic Scripted in Numerals Only |date=2013 |url=http://csi-india.org/ecommunications-may2013.html |page=1}}</ref> Karlamangalam Srikantaiah, the editor of the first edition, claims that the work may have been composed around 800 AD.<ref>[http://siri-bhoovalaya.org/muni-kumudendu/ Introduction to SiriBhoovalaya]</ref>

